Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
violationBrowser(25.10)                                violationBrowser(25.10)

Name
       violationBrowser - Displays a list of violations in the design database

Syntax
       violationBrowser

       [-help]

       [-aclimit]

       [-all]

       [-append]

       [-area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}]

       [-connectivity]

       [-density]

       [-displayByLayer]

       [-geometry]

       [-max_error_per_type <value>]

       [-no_display_false]

       [-overlap]

       [-process_antenna]

        [-search_desc]

       [-short]

       [-filter_query <LO_formula> | {-filter <filterString> -filter_mode {AND
       | OR | NOT}}]

       Displays a list of violations in the design database. The software gen-
       erates  markers  for the violations after you use one or more verifica-
       tion commands.

Geometry or Metal Density Violations
       Updates geometry and metal density violation markers incrementally dur-
       ing an Innovus session--that is, it displays the markers generated  the
       first  time  you  run  the verify_drc or verifyMetalDensity command and
       adds new markers, or deletes markers, on  subsequent  runs  during  the
       same  session. If the software finds violations during a subsequent run
       that were already  found  previously,  the  browser  display  does  not
       change, as there is no incremental update.

       The  browser  can make incremental changes because verify_drc and veri-
       fyMetalDensity can check a small area of  the  design  and  update  the
       database.  As a result of this behavior, the Innovus software saves the
       information from the first verification run.

Connectivity, Process Antennas, or AC Limit Violations
       Overwrites connectivity, process antenna, and AC limit violation  mark-
       ers  if  the  verifyConnectivity or verifyACLimit commands are run more
       than once during an Innovus session. These commands are net-based,  not
       area-based,  so the browser does not make incremental updates for them.
       As a result of this behavior, the Innovus software does  not  keep  the
       information from the first verification run.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes the type and default
              information for each violationBrowser parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and  all  its  parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man violationBrowser

       -aclimit
              Displays AC limit violations.

       -all   Displays all the violations that are present in the design. This
              is the default behavior.

       -append
              Appends  accumulated filtered markers to the existing markers in
              violation browser.

       -area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}
              Specifies the coordinates of the area whose violations  to  dis-
              play. For example, violationBrowser -area {0 0 100 100}.

       -connectivity
              Displays connectivity violations.

       -density
              Displays metal density violations.

       -displayByLayer
              Displays  the  list  of violations by the layer instead of route
              type.

       -filter <filterString>
              Specifies a text string  in  the  violation  message.  Violation
              Browser searches the message of each violation and displays only
              the violations whose messages match the search conditions.

              To specify a list of strings, separate each string with a space.

              To specify a literal string with space in it, enclose the string
              in double quotation marks.

              For example, you can specify strings such as the following:

              * METAL5

              * {"(600, 500)"}

              * {METAL3 "(700, 400)"}

              * "Pin of Net"

       -filter_mode {AND | OR | NOT}
              Specifies  the  condition  for searching multiple strings in the
              violation browser. You cannot filter complex expressions because
              the AND, OR, and NOT parameters are mutually exclusive.

              * The AND and OR conditions work on single strings  or  multiple
                strings.

              * The NOT condition works only on a single string.

       -filter_query <LO_formula>
              Specifies a complex logical expression for filtering violations.
              This  option  cannot be used along with -filter or -filter_mode.
              You can specify the AND, OR, and NOT conditions  in  the  search
              expression. Use:

              * && between strings in the expression to specify the AND condi-
                tion.

              * ||  between strings in the expression to specify the OR condi-
                tion.

              * ! before a string to specify the NOT condition. Note that ! is
                an one's complement operator. So for  example,  !{object(net1)
                && layer(m2)} is not allowed.

              The  -filter_query  parameter  supports  searches in the object,
              layer, and description areas. The area can  be  specified  using
              the object, layer, and desc keywords. For example:

              object(net1) || layer(m2) && desc(xxx)

              You can also use the wildcards * and ? in the search expression.
              For example:

              !object(clk*) && layer(m?)

              To specify a literal string with space in it, enclose the string
              in double quotation marks. For example:

              !object(clk*) && desc("prl spacing")

       -geometry
              Displays geometry violations.

       -max_error_per_type <value>
              Specifies  a  limit for the number of violations parsed for each
              violation  type.  For  example,  if  you  set   violationBrowser
              -max_error_per_type  500,  the Violation Browser parses and dis-
              plays only 500 markers per error type. Use this parameter if you
              are loading a large DRC file with millions of violations to pre-
              vent the databse from becoming slow while loading the  file  and
              to limit the number of violations you review in the browser.

              By default, the Violation Browser displays all markers.

       -no_display_false
              Prevents the Innovus software from displaying false violations.

       -overlap
              Displays overlaps in the design.

       -process_antenna
              Displays process antenna violations.

       -search_desc
              Searches for text in the violation message and the violation de-
              scription.

       -short Displays short violations.

Examples
              * The following command displays all violations whose marker ti-
                tle contains METAL3:

       violationBrowser -all -filter METAL3 -filter_mode OR

              * The  following  command  displays  geometry  violations  whose
                marker title contains METAL3 and tdsp:

       violationBrowser -geometry -filter {METAL3 tdsp} -filter_mode AND

              * The  following  command  displays  geometry  violations  whose
                marker title or marker description field contains Min and 0.24
                and METAL3:

       violationBrowser  -geometry  -filter {Min 0.24 METAL3} -filter_mode AND
       -search_desc

              * The following command displays violations occuring  on  Metal4
                or Metal5 layers but excludes short violations:

       violationBrowser -filter_query {!Short && (metal4 || metal5)}

Related Information
              * The  following  section  in the Identifying and Viewing Viola-
                tions chapter of User Guide.

                     * Viewing Violations With the Violation Browser

                     * Clearing Violations

              * "Evaluating Violations" in  the  Using  the  NanoRoute  Router
                chapter of User Guide.

